[src:george-davis-baseball/1900-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1900 throughout the world.
[src:george-davis-baseball/1901-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1901 throughout the world.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] After his playing career, Davis managed the Amherst College baseball team for several years.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] He died in a mental institution, suffering the effects of syphilis.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] Not much was known about Davis's life or career until the 1990s, when he gained some recognition from the city historian of his hometown of Cohoes, New York.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] He was elected to the Hall of Fame by the Veterans Committee in 1998.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] Born on August 23, 1870, in Cohoes, New York, Davis was one of seven children born to Abram and Sarah Davis.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] His father had immigrated from Wales and his mother came from England.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] Davis was playing amateur baseball in Albany when he was 16 years old and he could bat from both sides of the plate.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] By 1889, Davis was on a team of semiprofessional and amateur players near the Hudson River in Albany.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] The squad was managed by Tom York, a former major league player.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] York recommended Davis for major league service with the Cleveland Spiders.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] The team signed Davis for the 1890 season.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] Davis patrolled center field for the first two seasons of his career, leading the National League (NL) in outfield assists with 35 in 1890.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] He made three brief appearances as a pitcher in 1891, giving up seven earned runs in four innings and recording one save.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] That year he was among the league's top ten players in hits, doubles, triples, total bases, runs batted in (RBI), plate appearances and assists as an outfielder.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] Davis never appeared as a pitcher again, but his strong arm did lead the team to move him to third base in 1892, a position he played for the next five seasons.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] His batting average dropped almost 50 points to .241 in 1892, but he recorded 82 RBI and 36 stolen bases.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] The Spiders traded Davis to the New York Giants for aging star Buck Ewing shortly before the 1893 season, and Davis blossomed in New York City.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] With league rules moving the pitcher's mound back to 60 feet, 6 inches that season, offensive totals jumped across the league, and Davis was at the forefront of the surge.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] He compiled a .355 batting average and set career highs with 27 triples and 11 home runs.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] He also collected 22 doubles and 37 stolen bases, while scoring 112 runs and driving in 119.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] He became the first player to hit a triple and a home run in the same inning.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] Davis continued to perform at an elite level throughout the 1890s, regularly ranking among the league leaders in doubles, triples, RBI, and stolen bases.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] He had a batting average of more than .300 for nine consecutive seasons beginning in 1893.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] He began playing more shortstop in 1896 and moved to the position full-time the next season.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] In 1897, Davis hit .353 and registered a league-best 135 RBI.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] He led the league in double plays and fielding percentage four times each.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] During his playing career, Davis enjoyed a reputation as an intelligent and hard-working player who did not participate in dirty play.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] On their way to practice at the Polo Grounds on April 26, 1900, Davis and teammates Kid Gleason and Mike Grady stumbled upon a raging tenement fire.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] The players rushed into the building and rescued two women and a three-year-old child.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] I just went up the ladder the same as the rest of the boys and helped to carry down women and children...
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] I didn't do half as much as Grady and Gleason." His face blistered from the heat, Davis helped his team earn a 10–10 tie with the Boston Beaneaters that evening.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] The formation of the American League provided new financial opportunities to ballplayers, and induced by a $4,000 salary, Davis jumped to the Chicago White Sox in 1902.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] He became the first switch hitter to achieve 2,000 hits during the season.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] He attempted a return to the Giants the following season for a further raise to $6,700 (the second-highest figure in the league, after that of Nap Lajoie), but was prevented by the implementation of a peace agreement between the warring leagues.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] Davis sat out the bulk of the 1903 season before returning to the White Sox, with whom he spent the remainder of his career.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] His raw offensive statistics from this time pale before those of his earlier career, but when properly compared to a drastic league-wide decline in offense, they remain impressive.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] Davis stole home in Game 5 of the 1906 World Series for the champion White Sox.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] He also had three runs batted in for the Sox in the title-clinching Game 6 against the crosstown Chicago Cubs.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] His productivity declined in 1907, as he batted .238, his lowest batting average since 1892.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] He batted worse the following year, batting .217 in 128 games played.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] In 1909, he played just 28 games while batting .132 before he played his final game on August 15.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] His career totals in several statistical categories rank in the top 100 players all-time, including games played, at bats, hits, runs, doubles, triples, RBI and stolen bases.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] Davis returned to the minor leagues for one season as player-manager of the 1910 Des Moines Boosters.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] He managed a bowling alley in the early 1910s.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] He was the Amherst College baseball coach from 1913 to 1918, then he became a car salesman.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] The circumstances of his death remained a mystery until baseball historian Lee Allen discovered its details through a campaign to track down historical baseball players, run in part in *The Sporting News*.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] Davis was admitted to a Philadelphia mental institution in 1934 suffering from paresis due to tertiary syphilis.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] Davis was survived by his wife Jane, who was said to have been angry at him when he died.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] His wife spent $41 to have his body buried within a day at nearby Fernwood Cemetery.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] In a 1995 book, baseball author Bill James referred to Davis as baseball's best player who had not been inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] In 1997, baseball researcher Frederick Ivor-Campbell said that Davis was "the most neglected player of the 19th century.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] He's definitely the best eligible player not in the Hall, and he's a lot better than a lot of guys already in." Around the same time, Davis was rated the 21st best baseball player of all time in the official baseball encyclopedia, *Total Baseball*.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] Davis was up for a vote before the Hall of Fame's Veterans Committee in 1998.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] Before the committee voted, sportswriter Dave Anderson wrote an article in *The New York Times* on Davis's Hall of Fame candidacy.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] He pointed out the work of Cohoes city historian Walt Lipka, which favorably compared Davis to almost all of the shortstops in the Hall of Fame.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] Anderson supported Davis's election, saying, "It's as if he were discarded nearly a century ago into a time capsule that was forgotten until now...
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] For too long, George Stacey Davis has been his era's most forgotten best player." He was selected for induction that year.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] Prior to his Hall of Fame induction, a Society for American Baseball Research (SABR) chapter in New York put out a call to locate a descendant of Davis to be present at the induction ceremony and announced plans for a historical marker in Cohoes.
[src:george-davis-baseball/george-davis-baseball] As a great deal of time had passed since his death, no relatives could be located, but a group of about 50 people from Cohoes traveled to the ceremony in support of Davis.
